{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ca7b7f9d-7ba6-49a0-9fd4-4c372ee53f6b","content":"In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle events API** in `MauiProgram.cs` (or your app builder setup) via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* your code */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* your code */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* your code */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Use **platform `#if` directives** to keep platform-specific code separated.\n- `AddAndroid` / `AddiOS` expose native lifecycle methods (`OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnResume`, `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, etc.).\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` for the extension methods.\n- This approach keeps everything in shared code — no need for custom platform Activity or AppDelegate subclasses.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f6a18a29-137b-4476-b764-b276b61d941c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development. I can answer this directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":354,"requestId":"1124:1EB7C4:BD3167:DDC6C3:69FE85F7"},"id":"55b0cbc3-65e9-4ed0-a5ae-a24b6e9d3685","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:55:27.982Z","parentId":"88e557b5-0f3d-4843-a5a8-a560f32c21b8"}
